				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">What you describe is slowing the entire game to less than 60 fps. A few games did this, such as anything developed by Micronics, Bugs Bunny Birthday Blowout, every Super FX game that isn't Yoshi's Island, and almost all PlayStation and Nintendo 64 games. Some Game Boy games ran at a low frame rate to compensate for the original Game Boy's slow LCD, such as Balloon Kid (and its NES port Hello Kitty World).<br /><br />Other games update only half the objects each frame, such as enemies in Mega Man or explosions and smoke particles in Thwaite. Or they will run certain tasks only every few frames, such as the 21-frame IntervalTimerControl cycle of Super Mario Bros. or the 6-frame tenths cycle of Thwaite.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

